A formatting challenge using Pandas dataframes | By Sian Thompson¶

Image by Sharon Ang from Pixabay

Here's the Pandas problem:¶

A CSV report has been produced for the alphabet soup project <- link this.

However, there is a formatting problem with the file. When the sample report is read usineg the pandas dataframe, the last column - 'best_decrypted_word_dict' has been split accross several columns. The 4 dataframes below illustrate the problem.

It can be seen that this has also resulted in the misallocation of the 14 column names for the pandas dataframe.

The task is to fix the formatting problems for the pandas dataframe and output the report to a CSV named 'alphabet_soup_sample_report_fixed.csv'.

PLEASE NOTE

Scrolling down reveals the Solution section, so please take case of spoilers!!

This primarily lists steps which can be followed as a holistic hint to solving the problem

Here's the Solution:¶

Here are steps which may be followed:

  1. Read the dataframe and check the datatypes for the columns
  2. Store the column names in a variable called 'columns' for later use
  3. Convert the respective 'object' columns to string
  4. Concatenate the respective string columns under the 'best_decrypted_word_dict' column. Set the data type for the column as string.
  5. Drop the columns which are no longer needed and reset the column index
  6. Rename the columns and write to CSV
  7. Write the dataframe to a CSV called: 'alphabet_soup_sample_report_fixed.csv'

Read on to see an in-depth approach which follows these steps to solve the problem.

First of all, we notice there's some multi-indexing for the columns and the columns stored as objects which show key-pair values should be stored as strings rather than objects. I discovered that technically, pandas dataframes should not be used as pointers to dictionaries, and really it is best suited for dealing with numeric data. More information on this is available here: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/50731242/reading-pandas-dataframe-that-contains-dictionaries-in-cells-from-csv?rq=1

If storing thousands of records, I wouldn't store the word dictionary infromation. I captured it for the alphabet soup problem as it was at the heart of working towards solving the problem.

Notice at this stage...

  • inplace = True is passed as an argument to ensure the changes are made to the dataframe object.
  • Resetting the index means there's no longer a multi-index and we are left with 14 columns
  • Pandas has provided default names e.g. level_0 etc. to those columns which don't immediately have a name

However, remember we stored the column names in variable. Thus...
